The users spend an average 65.002 minutes on the website. The modal time is “62.26” “75.55” “77.05” “78.76” “84.53” The median time is 68.215. The distribution above is left-skewed. The highest frequency is 80 units of time(minutes).

library(caTools)

sample_data = sample.split(dummy_df2_norm, SplitRatio = 0.8)
train_data <- subset(dummy_df2_norm, sample_data == TRUE)
test_data <- subset(dummy_df2_norm, sample_data == FALSE)
create_train_test <- function(dummy_df2_norm, size = 0.8, train = TRUE) {
    n_row <- nrow(dummy_df2_norm)
    total_row <- size * n_row
    train_sample <- 1:total_row
    if (train == TRUE) {
        return (dummy_df2_norm[train_sample, ])
      } else {
        return (dummy_df2_norm[-train_sample, ])
     }
   }


create_train_test(dummy_df2_norm)

Variables that are closed to the center of the plot are less important for the first components. The most important pair is the Gender MALE VS FEMALE The Second most important pair is the Daily time spent on the site AND Daily Internet Usage Lastly, the third most important pair is the Age And Income

The Principal Components and how well they explain the variance

var <- get_pca_var(pca_residual)
head(var$contrib, 4)
##                                Dim.1      Dim.2      Dim.3     Dim.4      Dim.5

## Age                          1.445035
## X.Area.Income.               1.696498
## X.Daily.Internet.Usage.     17.500756

For the First principal component, the Daily internet usage and amount spent ont the site explain more that 50% of the variance. In the second principal component, the Daily internet usage and amount spent ont the site explain more that 9% of the variance In the Third Principal component, Age and income explain almost 100% of the valriance From this therefore, We can order the components based on how well they explain the variance as: a) Daily Internet Usage b) Daily time spent on the site c) Income d) Age

Summary Compasiron Between K-MEANS and HIERACHICAL clustering From the Analysis, we can identify that:

  1. K-means Cluster Analysis performs much better in identyfing patterns as compared to Hierrachical clustering.

  2. Since the dataset is large, visualizing hierrachical clusters is abit cumbersome as compared to K-means clustering.

  3. K-means clustering yields better reults using the optimal number of clusters which can be determined by Elbow and Silhouette Methods

  4. Clicking on an add is dependent on the gender of the respondent

  5. We can conclude that,The order of the factors that affect if a respondent clicks on an ad is: Gender Daily Internet Usage Daily time spent on the site Income Age
